Instead of `models.Manager`, you should be sub-classing &lt;a href=&quot;https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.2/topics/db/managers/#creating-a-manager-with-queryset-methods&quot;&gt;`models.QuerySet`&lt;/a&gt;:

    class MessageQuerySet(models.QuerySet):
        @property
        def unread_count(self):
            return self.filter(read=False).count()

Then use the &lt;a href=&quot;https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.2/ref/models/querysets/#django.db.models.query.QuerySet.as_manager&quot;&gt;`as_manager`&lt;/a&gt; method in your model:

    class Message(models.Model):
        ...
    
        objects = MessageQuerySet.as_manager()

If you need to add methods to both the `QuerySet` returned from the manager, and the manager itself, you will need to use &lt;a href=&quot;https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.2/topics/db/managers/#from-queryset&quot;&gt;`from_queryset`&lt;/a&gt;:

    class MessageManager(models.Manager):
        def some_manager_only_method(self):
            print(&#39;do stuff&#39;)
    
    class MessageQuerySet(models.QuerySet):
        @property
        def unread_count(self):
            return self.filter(read=False).count()
    
    class Message(models.Model):
        ...
    
        objects = MessageManager.from_queryset(MessageQuerySet)()

